      <h2 class="element-invisible">You are here</h2><ul class="breadcrumb"><li><a href="/front">Home</a></li><li><a href="/reviews">Reviews</a></li></ul>      <a id="main-content"></a>
                    <h1>Digital Sampling: The Design And Use Of Music Technologies</h1>
                                          <article id="node-4927447" class="node node--article node--full node--article--full clearfix" about="/reviews/digital-sampling-design-and-use-music-technologies" typeof="sioc:Item foaf:Document" role="article" class="node node--article node--full node--article--full">
      
  <div class="node--content-wrapper">
    <div class="node--inner-wrapper">
    
      
    <span property="dc:title" content="Digital Sampling: The Design And Use Of Music Technologies" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>
    
    <div  class="node__content">
	  <div class="group-header">
  <span class="field--subtitle">
    Book Review  </span>

  <ul class="field--subject"><li><a href="/reviews/media">Media</a> > <a href="/reviews/media/book-ebook">Book / eBook</a></li></ul><span class="field--author">By <a href="/author/rob-puricelli">Rob Puricelli</a></span>
  <div class="field--issue-date">
    Published <a href="/magazine/2022-06">June 2022</a>  </div>
</div><p class="nindent">When it comes to history, there are typically two ways of looking at aÂ subject. One is to examine it from an emotional perspective, waxing lyrical with anecdotes, tall tales and very much through roseâtinted glasses. The other is to forensically examine the facts, seek out firstâperson testimonies, check, verify, corroborate and verify again all of the dates, persons, locations and details, referencing sources meticulously so that no doubt and no emotion remain. Of course, itâs often the case that the sweet spot between both these methods is where balance is achieved. For example, the origin of the first ever digital sample captured by the inventors of the Fairlight CMI is rarely called into question, with all parties agreeing what the sample source was. How that sample was captured, on the other hand, and by whom, is not so crystal clear.</p>

<p><span class="media-image-right"><a href="https://dt7v1i9vyp3mf.cloudfront.net/styles/news_large/s3/imagelibrary/d/digital_sampling_book_01-719xnC2mGxegSiRV6FdQS0GVwhoDKKWV.jpg" title="" class="colorbox" data-colorbox-gallery="all" data-cbox-img-attrs="{&quot;title&quot;: &quot;&quot;, &quot;alt&quot;: &quot;Book cover - Digital Sampling: The Design And Use Of Music Technologies&quot;}"><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://dt7v1i9vyp3mf.cloudfront.net/styles/news_preview/s3/imagelibrary/d/digital_sampling_book_01-yv72YSbdNeKqoMtYhK3xN.mWuZsaDjUZ.jpg" width="200" height="300" alt="Book cover - Digital Sampling: The Design And Use Of Music Technologies" title="" /></a></span>It is this kind of quandary, along with many other key and crucial moments in the history of the birth of digital sampling, that Paul Harkins, lecturer in the music department at Edinburgh Napier University, seeks to reveal the truth about in his book <em>Digital Sampling: The Design And Use Of Music Technologies</em> (Routledge, ISBN 9780815381648)Â âÂ and he does so without sacrificing the magic of the anecdotal yarns spun by people who were around at the time.</p>

<p>He rightly starts with the Fairlight CMI; this was the worldâs first commercially available digital sampler. He covers the initial impact of the Series IÂ and II, before moving on to the impact of PageÂ R, the first onâscreen, computerâbased sequencer, how looping delivered aÂ new way of making music, and then the pristine qualities of the 16âbit, 100kHz Series III. He then addresses the next big player in the sampling arena, Dave Rossumâs Eâmu, and looks at the various sampleâbased tools that they developed throughout the â80s, such as the Emulator sampling keyboard and their more rhythmâ and loopâfocused SP range.</p>

<p>But, fascinating as it is, this book does not simply wallow in the history of sampling. The second half of the book takes in four case studies, looking at artists that use sampling in fascinating ways, taking in such people and topics as Akufen and Todd Edwards and their use of micro sampling; foot pedals and folk music as used by King Creosote; the use of found sounds by aptlyânamed Edinburgh collective Found; and the highly constrained yet utterly fascinating methods employed by Matthew Herbert, who uses aÂ set of hugely restrictive, selfâimposed rules when looking for sample sources that results in aÂ form of modern musique concrÃ¨te.</p>

<p>The text is supported not only by aÂ range of great photographs and images of advertisements from back in the dayÂ âÂ these help to conjure up the magic and wonder of what was aÂ groundâbreaking technology at the timeÂ âÂ but also aÂ large number of quotes from proponents and key players involved in the invention, creation and use of samplers. Many of these derive from interviews conducted by Paul himself, including with Peter Vogel, Kim Ryrie, JJÂ Jeczalik, Arthur Baker, Peter Howell, Richard James Burgess, Dave Rossum, Scott Wedge, and many more.</p>

<p>As youâd expect from aÂ book rooted in the academic world, thereâs aÂ plethora of footnotes and references, as well as an extensive bibliography that could aid you in your own research or simply serve to underline the extensive research that underpins this publication.</p>

<p>I often find myself at odds with the academic world when it comes to the way music technology is studied and portrayed. As someone who uses these machines, restores them and waxes lyrical about them to anyone who cares to listen, IÂ often find academic research into these things rather sterile, devoid of feeling and, in some cases, quite flowery and off the mark, hypothesising as some do about the intentions of the inventors or users. Quite often, those that created or used these marvellous tools had no ambition or higher calling other than to enable or be enabled by some brilliant technology that allowed them to create something exciting. To imply some ulterior motive beyond that can sometimes be to gloss over the very base and instinctual urge to simply have fun making music.</p>

<blockquote>IÂ often find academic research into these things rather sterile, devoid of feeling, quite flowery and off the mark... Harkins avoidsÂ this.</blockquote>

<p>Harkins avoids this by speaking to the protagonists, rather than speculating; by referencing their work directly and piecing together various parts of history. The reader comes away with aÂ much clearer narrative on the subject and aÂ solid understanding of how much of an impact sampling has had since Vogel &amp; Ryrie cooked it up as aÂ âworkaroundâ on their firstâiteration Fairlight CMI. It is astounding that this soâcalled âcheatâ literally changed the way we make music forever, spawned aÂ vast array of other musicâmaking tools, established aÂ whole new way for lawyers to make money, and became the global standard in audio and music technology that it is today.</p>

<p>Although this book is not in the same realm as something written by, say, Simon Reynolds or Jon Savage, which weaves aÂ fantastic tale through music history, it still manages to lead the reader on aÂ hugely interesting journey into the birth of sampling, involving the key movers and players, whilst also exploring how far the medium has evolved since then. For anyone with even aÂ remote interest in digital sampling âÂ academic, synthâgeek or otherwise âÂ itâs aÂ great read from beginning to end.</p>
<div class="infobox">
	<h3>Information</h3>

	<div class="uk">
		<p class="infop">Paperback or eBook Â£27.99. Hardback Â£96.</p>

		<p class="infow"><a href="https://www.routledge.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noreferrer noopener">www.routledge.com</a></p>
	</div>

	<div class="us">
		<p class="infop">Paperback or eBook $37.56. Hardback $128.</p>

		<p class="infow"><a href="https://www.routledge.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noreferrer noopener">www.routledge.com</a></p>
	</div>
</div>
